From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: experintellia <280144245+experintellia@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Wed, 8 Jul 2026 00:09:43 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 09/41] web-app: show a focus outline on search fields
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The global input[type='text']:focus outline never applied to the
search inputs (they carry no type attribute), and _search-input.scss
set outline: none on top — so nothing indicated whether the search
field had focus. Reuse the app's standard focus outline instead.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 packages/frontend/scss/misc/_search-input.scss | 10 ++++++++--
 1 file changed, 8 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/packages/frontend/scss/misc/_search-input.scss b/packages/frontend/scss/misc/_search-input.scss
index 0a39d14ac..328e23719 100644
--- a/packages/frontend/scss/misc/_search-input.scss
+++ b/packages/frontend/scss/misc/_search-input.scss
@@ -1,3 +1,5 @@
+@use '../variables';
+
 input.search-input {
   overflow: hidden;
   text-overflow: ellipsis;
@@ -13,8 +15,12 @@ input.search-input {
   background-color: transparent;
   caret-color: var(--navBarSearchPlaceholder);
   color: var(--globalText);
-  // A blinking cursor is enough in terms of visibility. Or is it??
-  outline: none;
+  // slothfulchat: these inputs carry no `type` attribute, so the global
+  // input[type='text']:focus outline never matches them — restore it here
+  // instead of the old `outline: none`.
+  &:focus {
+    outline: 1px solid variables.$color-global-textarea-outline;
+  }
 
   &.wrap {
     margin-inline-start: 40px;
